<subSubSection id="F7D86578FFB61B01FDDEFDE9017444D8" pageId="8" pageNumber="158" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="BF7D36F3FFB61B01FDDEFDE9017444D8" blockId="8.[452,1846,396,750]" pageId="8" pageNumber="158">
A widely distributed species, black with a red spot on humeri of elytra. Occurs in 
<collectingCountry id="C7D57663FFB61B01FD53FD3B04064488" box="[649,768,654,702]" name="Samoa" pageId="8" pageNumber="158">Samoa</collectingCountry>
, Tahiti, 
<collectingCountry id="C7D57663FFB61B01FC7FFD3B034A4488" box="[933,1100,654,702]" name="Indonesia" pageId="8" pageNumber="158">Moluccas</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingRegion id="7D06F811FFB61B01FBBFFD3B03B14488" box="[1125,1207,654,702]" country="Indonesia" name="Jawa Timur" pageId="8" pageNumber="158">Java</collectingRegion>
, Borneo, 
<collectingCountry id="C7D57663FFB61B01FAA8FD3B02EA4488" box="[1394,1516,654,702]" name="Sri Lanka" pageId="8" pageNumber="158">Ceylon</collectingCountry>
, and 
<collectingCountry id="C7D57663FFB61B01F980FD3B00374488" box="[1626,1841,654,702]" name="Madagascar" pageId="8" pageNumber="158">Madagascar</collectingCountry>
. We found it common in 
<collectingCountry id="C7D57663FFB61B01FC5BFD7104EA44D8" box="[897,1004,708,750]" name="Guam" pageId="8" pageNumber="158">Guam</collectingCountry>
, under bark of felled trees, in 1936.
</paragraph>
